{"accepted":[{"assertion":"AI-contributions wiki claim — wiki: Full solution (stronger than literature).","id":"vf_0ecc6a03dfb3cc0e","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"},{"assertion":"Erdős 650, axis-3 divergence: the hosted Lean proof does not certify the informal lower-bound argument it formalizes. The informal proof (GPT 5.4 Pro, prompted by He, Li, and Tang) contained a gap; Aristotle's formalization repaired it in-flight, and the gap surfaced only in the authors' arXiv write-up. Recorded per sources/informal_notes.yaml; source https://www.erdosproblems.com/forum/thread/650","id":"vf_1966da74c332bfda","trust":"signed","type":"tension"},{"assertion":"Hosted Lean proof: jayyhk proof of 650 (state complete) https://github.com/Jayyhk/erdos-lean/blob/main/problems/650/Erdos650.lean.","id":"vf_9aad11b50363b593","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"},{"assertion":"Erdős Problem #650: declared status 'solved'. Formalized: no. Let $f(m)$ be such that if $A\\subseteq \\{1,\\ldots,N\\}$ has $\\lvert A\\rvert=m$ then every interval in $[1,\\infty)$ of length $2N$ contains $\\geq f(m)$ many distinct integers $b_1,\\ldots,b_r$ where each $b_i$ is divisible by some $a_i\\in A$, where $a_1,\\ldots,a_r$ are distinct.\n\nEstimate $f(m)$. In particular is it true that $f(m)\\ll m^{1/2}$? Prize: no. OEIS: A027434. Tags: number theory.","id":"vf_b872635e4c48b5a6","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"},{"assertion":"Hosted Lean proof: plby proof of 650 (state complete) https://github.com/plby/lean-proofs/blob/main/src/v4.29.1/ErdosProblems/Erdos650.lean.","id":"vf_c52a29a640a8866c","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"},{"assertion":"Formal-Conjectures statement: FC 650 (PR #4081) [in-pr] https://github.com/google-deepmind/formal-conjectures/pull/4081.","id":"vf_f9b1db91b064aa3d","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"}],"accepted_activity":false,"activity":[{"accepted":false,"claim":"Pinned Formal Conjectures activity classification; integration activity does not establish mathemati